      <li>TEMPERATURE : [&acirc;&dagger;&lsquo; in inflammatory swelling]</li>
      <li>PULSE : [&acirc;&dagger;&lsquo;in inflammatory swelling]<strong>Liebermeister's
          rule</strong>&Acirc;&nbsp;concerns the increment ratio between and
        adult individual's cardiac frequency and temperature when in fever. Each
        Celsius grade of&Acirc;&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thermoregulation">body
          temperature</a>increment corresponds to an 8&Acirc;&nbsp;<em>beats per
          minute</em>&Acirc;&nbsp;increase in cardiac frequency.<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Liebermeister%27s_rule#cite_note-1"><sup>[1]</sup></a><a

          href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Liebermeister%27s_rule#cite_note-2"><sup>[2]</sup></a>&Acirc;&nbsp;An
        exception to this rule by creating a&Acirc;&nbsp;<strong>relative</strong>&Acirc;&nbsp;<a

          href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bradycardia">bradycardia</a>&Acirc;&nbsp;is
        known as&Acirc;&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Faget_sign">Fagetsign</a>&Acirc;&nbsp;(pulse-temperature
        dissociation) common in some diseases, especially&Acirc;&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yellow_fever">yellow
          fever</a>&Acirc;&nbsp;and salmonella typhi
        <ol>
