    <p> <strong>Aortic unfolding</strong>&Acirc;&nbsp;is an old term that was
      used to describe the&Acirc;&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radiological">radiological</a>&Acirc;&nbsp;<a

        href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abnormal">abnormality</a>&Acirc;&nbsp;on&Acirc;&nbsp;<a

        href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chest_X-ray">chest X-ray</a>&Acirc;&nbsp;that
      show widening of the&Acirc;&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mediastinum">mediastinum</a>&Acirc;&nbsp;which
      might look like&Acirc;&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thoracic_aortic_aneurysm">thoracic
        aortic aneurysm</a>.<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aortic_unfolding#cite_note-1"><sup>[1]</sup></a>&Acirc;&nbsp;With
      aging the length increases by approximately 12% per decade, whereas the
      diameter increases by just 3% per decade. This elongation causes the
      descending aorta to appear as a vertical shadow on the left&Acirc;&nbsp;<a

        href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heart">heart</a>&Acirc;&nbsp;border.<a

        href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aortic_unfolding#cite_note-2"><sup>[2]</sup></a>&Acirc;&nbsp;Aortic
      unfolding, though not serious, should be differentiated from the more
      severe dissection of the&Acirc;&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aorta">aorta</a>.</p>
